{"type":"message","id":"03ea57f8","parentId":"b8108390","timestamp":"2026-03-23T00:47:12.083Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_lado0j9xeu9e_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import \"../../github-copilot-token-bJVPdSYE.js\";\nimport { Ct as resolveAgentWorkspaceDir, bt as resolveAgentIdByWorkspacePath, ot as writeFileWithinRoot } from \"../../query-expansion-DnS6CGY2.js\";\nimport { c as resolveStateDir } from \"../../paths-BwJ6yG6k.js\";\nimport { t as createSubsystemLogger } from \"../../subsystem-CDcEQtQK.js\";\nimport { J as toAgentStoreSessionKey, U as resolveAgentIdFromSessionKey, it as parseAgentSessionKey } from \"../../workspace-Cg3kGb1y.js\";\nimport \"../../logger-C0l_Gj8Y.js\";\nimport { ar as hasInterSessionUserProvenance } from \"../../model-selection-CU2b7bN6.js\";\nimport \"../../boolean-Cuaw_-7j.js\";\nimport \"../../fetch-BsqGaLgN.js\";\nimport \"../../frontmatter-D6-ANhh_.js\";\nimport { generateSlugViaLLM } from \"../../llm-slug-generator.js\";\nimport { t as resolveHookConfig } from \"../../config-BYkzFD4a.js\";\nimport fs from \"node:fs/promises\";\nimport os from \"node:os\";\nimport path from \"node:path\";\n//#region src/hooks/bundled/session-memory/handler.ts\n/**\n* Session memory hook handler\n*\n* Saves session context to memory when /new or /reset command is triggered\n* Creates a new dated memory file with LLM-generated slug\n*/\nconst log = createSubsystemLogger(\"hooks/session-memory\");\nfunction resolveDisplaySessionKey(params) {\n\tif (!params.cfg || !params.workspaceDir) return params.sessionKey;\n\tconst workspaceAgentId = resolveAgentIdByWorkspacePath(params.cfg, params.workspaceDir);\n\tconst parsed = parseAgentSessionKey(params.sessionKey);\n\tif (!workspaceAgentId || !parsed || workspaceAgentId === parsed.agentId) return params.sessionKey;\n\treturn toAgentStoreSessionKey({\n\t\tagentId: workspaceAgentId,\n\t\trequestKey: parsed.rest\n\t});\n}\n/**\n* Read recent messages from session file for slug generation\n*/\nasync function getRecentSessionContent(sessionFilePath, messageCount = 15) {\n\ttry {\n\t\tconst lines = (await fs.readFile(sessionFilePath, \"utf-8\")).trim().split(\"\\n\");\n\t\tconst allMessages = [];\n\t\tfor (const line of lines) try {\n\t\t\tconst entry = JSON.parse(line);\n\t\t\tif (entry.type === \"message\" && entry.message) {\n\t\t\t\tconst msg = entry.message;\n\t\t\t\tconst role = msg.role;\n\t\t\t\tif ((role === \"user\" || role === \"assistant\") && msg.content) {\n\t\t\t\t\tif (role === \"user\" && hasInterSessionUserProvenance(msg)) continue;\n\t\t\t\t\tconst text = Array.isArray(msg.content) ? msg.content.find((c) => c.type === \"text\")?.text : msg.content;\n\t\t\t\t\tif (text && !text.startsWith(\"/\")) allMessages.push(`${role}: ${text}`);\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t} catch {}\n\t\treturn allMessages.slice(-messageCount).join(\"\\n\");\n\t} catch {\n\t\treturn null;\n\t}\n}\n/**\n* Try the active transcript first; if /new already rotated it,\n* fallback to the latest .jsonl.reset.* sibling.\n*/\nasync function getRecentSessionContentWithResetFallback(sessionFilePath, messageCount = 15) {\n\tconst primary = await getRecentSessionContent(sessionFilePath, messageCount);\n\tif (primary) return primary;\n\ttry {\n\t\tconst dir = path.dirname(sessionFilePath);\n\t\tconst resetPrefix = `${path.basename(sessionFilePath)}.reset.`;\n\t\tconst resetCandidates = (await fs.readdir(dir)).filter((name) => name.startsWith(resetPrefix)).toSorted();\n\t\tif (resetCandidates.length === 0) return primary;\n\t\tconst latestResetPath = path.join(dir, resetCandidates[resetCandidates.length - 1]);\n\t\tconst fallback = await getRecentSessionContent(latestResetPath, messageCount);\n\t\tif (fallback) log.debug(\"Loaded session content from reset fallback\", {\n\t\t\tsessionFilePath,\n\t\t\tlatestResetPath\n\t\t});\n\t\treturn fallback || primary;\n\t} catch {\n\t\treturn primary;\n\t}\n}\nfunction stripResetSuffix(fileName) {\n\tconst resetIndex = fileName.indexOf(\".reset.\");\n\treturn resetIndex === -1 ? fileName : fileName.slice(0, resetIndex);\n}\nasync function findPreviousSessionFile(params) {\n\ttry {\n\t\tconst files = await fs.readdir(params.sessionsDir);\n\t\tconst fileSet = new Set(files);\n\t\tconst baseFromReset = params.currentSessionFile ? stripResetSuffix(path.basename(params.currentSessionFile)) : void 0;\n\t\tif (baseFromReset && fileSet.has(baseFromReset)) return path.join(params.sessionsDir, baseFromReset);\n\t\tconst trimmedSessionId = params.sessionId?.trim();\n\t\tif (trimmedSessionId) {\n\t\t\tconst canonicalFile = `${trimmedSessionId}.jsonl`;\n\t\t\tif (fileSet.has(canonicalFile)) return path.join(params.sessionsDir, canonicalFile);\n\t\t\tconst topicVariants = files.filter((name) => name.startsWith(`${trimmedSessionId}-topic-`) && name.endsWith(\".jsonl\") && !name.includes(\".reset.\")).toSorted().toReversed();\n\t\t\tif (topicVariants.length > 0) return path.join(params.sessionsDir, topicVariants[0]);\n\t\t}\n\t\tif (!params.currentSessionFile) return;\n\t\tconst nonResetJsonl = files.filter((name) => name.endsWith(\".jsonl\") && !name.includes(\".reset.\")).toSorted().toReversed();\n\t\tif (nonResetJsonl.length > 0) return path.join(params.sessionsDir, nonResetJsonl[0]);\n\t} catch {}\n}\n/**\n* Save session context to memory when /new or /reset command is triggered\n*/\nconst saveSessionToMemory = async (event) => {\n\tconst isResetCommand = event.action === \"new\" || event.action === \"reset\";\n\tif (event.type !== \"command\" || !isResetCommand) return;\n\ttry {\n\t\tlog.debug(\"Hook triggered for reset/new command\", { action: event.action });\n\t\tconst context = event.context || {};\n\t\tconst cfg = context.cfg;\n\t\tconst contextWorkspaceDir = typeof context.workspaceDir === \"string\" && context.workspaceDir.trim().length > 0 ? context.workspaceDir : void 0;\n\t\tconst agentId = resolveAgentIdFromSessionKey(event.sessionKey);\n\t\tconst workspaceDir = contextWorkspaceDir || (cfg ? resolveAgentWorkspaceDir(cfg, agentId) : path.join(resolveStateDir(process.env, os.homedir), \"workspace\"));\n\t\tconst displaySessionKey = resolveDisplaySessionKey({\n\t\t\tcfg,\n\t\t\tworkspaceDir: contextWorkspaceDir,\n\t\t\tsessionKey: event.sessionKey\n\t\t});\n\t\tconst memoryDir = path.join(workspaceDir, \"memory\");\n\t\tawait fs.mkdir(memoryDir, { recursive: true });\n\t\tconst now = new Date(event.timestamp);\n\t\tconst dateStr = now.toISOString().split(\"T\")[0];\n\t\tconst sessionEntry = context.previousSessionEntry || context.sessionEntry || {};\n\t\tconst currentSessionId = sessionEntry.sessionId;\n\t\tlet currentSessionFile = sessionEntry.sessionFile || void 0;\n\t\tif (!currentSessionFile || currentSessionFile.includes(\".reset.\")) {\n\t\t\tconst sessionsDirs = /* @__PURE__ */ new Set();\n\t\t\tif (currentSessionFile) sessionsDirs.add(path.dirname(currentSessionFile));\n\t\t\tsessionsDirs.add(path.join(workspaceDir, \"sessions\"));\n\t\t\tfor (const sessionsDir of sessionsDirs) {\n\t\t\t\tconst recoveredSessionFile = await findPreviousSessionFile({\n\t\t\t\t\tsessionsDir,\n\t\t\t\t\tcurrentSessionFile,\n\t\t\t\t\tsessionId: currentSessionId\n\t\t\t\t});\n\t\t\t\tif (!recoveredSessionFile) continue;\n\t\t\t\tcurrentSessionFile = recoveredSessionFile;\n\t\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Found previous session file\", { file: currentSessionFile });\n\t\t\t\tbreak;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t\tlog.debug(\"Session context resolved\", {\n\t\t\tsessionId: currentSessionId,\n\t\t\tsessionFile: currentSessionFile,\n\t\t\thasCfg: Boolean(cfg)\n\t\t});\n\t\tconst sessionFile = currentSessionFile || void 0;\n\t\tconst hookConfig = resolveHookConfig(cfg, \"session-memory\");\n\t\tconst messageCount = typeof hookConfig?.messages === \"number\" && hookConfig.messages > 0 ? hookConfig.messages : 15;\n\t\tlet slug = null;\n\t\tlet sessionContent = null;\n\t\tif (sessionFile) {\n\t\t\tsessionContent = await getRecentSessionContentWithResetFallback(sessionFile, messageCount);\n\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Session content loaded\", {\n\t\t\t\tlength: sessionContent?.length ?? 0,\n\t\t\t\tmessageCount\n\t\t\t});\n\t\t\tconst allowLlmSlug = !(process.env.OPENCLAW_TEST_FAST === \"1\" || process.env.VITEST === \"true\" || process.env.VITEST === \"1\" || false) && hookConfig?.llmSlug !== false;\n\t\t\tif (sessionContent && cfg && allowLlmSlug) {\n\t\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Calling generateSlugViaLLM...\");\n\t\t\t\tslug = await generateSlugViaLLM({\n\t\t\t\t\tsessionContent,\n\t\t\t\t\tcfg\n\t\t\t\t});\n\t\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Generated slug\", { slug });\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t\tif (!slug) {\n\t\t\tslug = now.toISOString().split(\"T\")[1].split(\".\")[0].replace(/:/g, \"\").slice(0, 4);\n\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Using fallback timestamp slug\", { slug });\n\t\t}\n\t\tconst filename = `${dateStr}-${slug}.md`;\n\t\tconst memoryFilePath = path.join(memoryDir, filename);\n\t\tlog.debug(\"Memory file path resolved\", {\n\t\t\tfilename,\n\t\t\tpath: memoryFilePath.replace(os.homedir(), \"~\")\n\t\t});\n\t\tconst timeStr = now.toISOString().split(\"T\")[1].split(\".\")[0];\n\t\tconst sessionId = sessionEntry.sessionId || \"unknown\";\n\t\tconst source = context.commandSource || \"unknown\";\n\t\tconst entryParts = [\n\t\t\t`# Session: ${dateStr} ${timeStr} UTC`,\n\t\t\t\"\",\n\t\t\t`- **Session Key**: ${displaySessionKey}`,\n\t\t\t`- **Session ID**: ${sessionId}`,\n\t\t\t`- **Source**: ${source}`,\n\t\t\t\"\"\n\t\t];\n\t\tif (sessionContent) entryParts.push(\"## Conversation Summary\", \"\", sessionContent, \"\");\n\t\tawait writeFileWithinRoot({\n\t\t\trootDir: memoryDir,\n\t\t\trelativePath: filename,\n\t\t\tdata: entryParts.join(\"\\n\"),\n\t\t\tencoding: \"utf-8\"\n\t\t});\n\t\tlog.debug(\"Memory file written successfully\");\n\t\tconst relPath = memoryFilePath.replace(os.homedir(), \"~\");\n\t\tlog.info(`Session context saved to ${relPath}`);\n\t} catch (err) {\n\t\tif (err instanceof Error) log.error(\"Failed to save session memory\", {\n\t\t\terrorName: err.name,\n\t\t\terrorMessage: err.message,\n\t\t\tstack: err.stack\n\t\t});\n\t\telse log.error(\"Failed to save session memory\", { error: String(err) });\n\t}\n};\n//#endregion\nexport { saveSessionToMemory as default };\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774226832078}}
{"type":"message","id":"86be04a1","parentId":"03ea57f8","timestamp":"2026-03-23T00:48:23.344Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The `session-memory` hook:\n1. Gets the previous session's transcript (JSONL)\n2. Extracts the last 15 messages\n3. Saves them to `memory/YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md`\n\nBut it doesn't inject this into the next session. The new session starts with zero context from the previous conversation.\n\nWhat I need to do is:\n1. Modify the session-memory hook OR create a companion hook that ALSO writes a \"LAST_SESSION_TRANSCRIPT.md\" file with the raw transcript content (not just a summary)\n2. Then modify the session startup to read this file and inject it into context\n\nThe cleanest approach:\n\n\n1. Write a custom hook that runs on `command:new`, reads the previous session's full transcript, and saves it to `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` with a header indicating this is the previous session's context\n2. Modify AGENTS.md startup to read `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` if it exists and includes it in context\n\nThe challenge is that the session startup runs before I have a chance to inject content into the system prompt. I need to figure out how to get this file content into the context window itself.\n\nLooking at how the session startup works, it reads SOUL.md, USER.md, and other files directly into context. But these are static files—there's no way to dynamically inject a file's content into the context unless it's already part of the workspace files that get loaded.\n\nWhat if I write the previous session's context to a file that gets loaded at startup, like a dedicated memory file that the startup sequence reads? The issue is that OpenClaw only loads specific named files, not arbitrary ones.\n\nActually, the `agent:bootstrap` hook might be the key here—it can modify `context.bootstrapFiles` to inject additional files into the context. But that only fires during gateway startup, not when individual sessions start. The real challenge is that there's no built-in hook for `session:start` that would let me inject content when a new session begins.\n\nI could create a custom hook that fires on `command:new`, but the problem is that when a new session starts after `/new`, the context gets reset—the hook runs in the old session's context, and there's no way to pass information to the new session that follows.\n\nWhat if I save the previous session's content to a file, then modify the startup sequence to always check for and inject that file's content at the beginning of each conversation? The tricky part is that the startup sequence runs on every message, not just the first one of a new session, so I'd need a way to detect whether this is actually a new session versus just another message in the current session.\n\nLooking at the session lifecycle, `/new` creates a fresh session with a new sessionId, so I could track that in the startup sequence and only inject the saved content when the sessionId has actually changed. The problem is I don't have direct access to the sessionId from within the agent code itself—it's only available in the system prompt metadata.\n\nActually, I can see the session key and model info in the runtime section, but the sessionId isn't exposed there. So I'd need to either save the sessionId to a file and compare it on the next startup, or find another way to detect when `/new` has actually been called.\n\nThe simplest approach might be to track this at the hook level. When `/new` is called, I can save the previous session's transcript to a file, and when the agent starts up, it checks if that file exists and injects the context from there.\n\nThe challenge is that after `/new`, the startup sequence runs and reads various memory files, but there's no automatic mechanism to pull in the previous session's transcript. The startup reads AGENTS.md, SOUL.md, and other context files, but the session transcript isn't part of that.\n\nI'm thinking the most practical solution is to create a hook that fires on `command:new` to save the session context, then modify the session startup to check for that saved context and inject it if found. The tricky part is figuring out how to pass the previous session's context to the new session without the agent having to explicitly ask for it.\n\nLooking at how the hooks system works, the `agent:bootstrap` hook fires before the agent starts and can modify the bootstrap context. If I create a hook that runs during the bootstrap phase, it could inject the previous session's saved content directly into the context for the new session.\n\nThe challenge is that `agent:bootstrap` only fires on gateway startup, not when individual sessions start. I need to find a way to trigger context injection on session initialization. Let me reconsider the architecture—maybe the approach is to have the hook save the context to a file, then modify the agent to read that file at the start of each session.\n\nI'm exploring whether a startup script or system event could handle this, but that seems overly complex. The most straightforward solution would be modifying the session-memory hook itself to also inject the context, but since that's a bundled hook I can't edit, I need a different approach.\n\nLet me create a custom hook that runs on the `command:new` event. The hook would capture the previous session's context and write it to a file in the workspace. Then during session startup, the agent checks for that file and injects its contents as the initial context for the new session. the sessionId is stored separately. On the next startup, I need to figure out if the session has actually changed since the last message. The session key stays `agent:main:main`, but the sessionId itself changes when `/new` is called. The issue is that at startup I'm reading files, not yet in a session, so I don't have the current sessionId yet to compare against what's stored.\n\nI could store the sessionId after each message is processed, then compare on the next startup to detect if we're in a fresh session. Or simpler: just check at the end of processing whether the sessionId has changed from the previous message.\n\nActually, the most straightforward approach would be to always inject the previous session's context at the start of a new session—I don't need to perfectly detect whether it's new, I just need to inject the saved context when appropriate. The question becomes whether there's a lightweight way to handle this without requiring explicit user prompting.\n\nLet me reconsider: what if instead of trying to inject context at startup, I just make the previous session's transcript available as a file the agent can read? The hook saves to `memory/LAST_SESSION.md`, and during AGENTS.md startup I check if that file exists and read it—but that approach is too heavy since it runs on every message, not just at session initialization.\n\nActually, I think the cleaner solution is simpler: have the hook save the previous session's context with its sessionId, and at the start of each new session, inject that saved context so the agent immediately knows what was discussed before without having to read a file.\n\nThe tricky part is timing—when the session starts and AGENTS.md runs, the sessionId hasn't been set yet from the first user message. So I need to track the sessionId separately: save it at the end of each message, then on the next startup compare the saved sessionId against the current one to determine if this is actually a new session.\n\nThe simplest approach might be a hook that fires on `command:new` to capture the previous session's content, then another hook or system that loads that saved context into the next session. But I'm realizing OpenClaw might not have a built-in mechanism to automatically inject saved session context on startup—it would need to be explicitly triggered or the context would need to persist differently.\n\nLet me step back and think about what actually happens when `/new` is called. The session gets a fresh ID, but the actual content injection happens when the next user message arrives, which is when the system prompt and context are built. So if I can hook into that moment—right when the first message in a new session is being processed—I could inject the previous session's saved context at that point.\n\nThe real problem is that session startup happens before I have any context about what the user wants to do. So instead of trying to inject context automatically, what if I save the session context to a file when `/new` is called, and then when the user sends their first message, I check for that file and include it automatically? That way the context is there when they start the new conversation.\n\nBut here's the thing—I'm already reading memory files at startup based on what's in the system prompt. The session key doesn't change after `/new`, just the sessionId. So the challenge is figuring out how to detect that a new session has started and load the right context at that moment.\n\nActually, I think I've been overcomplicating this. The hook has access to `context.previousSessionEntry`, which means I can grab the previous session's information right when `/new` is called. I should write that context to a file from the hook itself, and then during startup I can check if we're in a fresh session and load that file automatically. The key is comparing the current sessionId against what was stored previously—if they match, we're in the same session and don't need to inject old context; if they differ, we're in a new session and should pull in the saved content.\n\nThe tricky part is that during the initial startup sequence, I don't have access to the current sessionId yet, so I can't do the comparison right away. I need to store the sessionId at the end of each message processing, then check it at the start of the next one. Alternatively, I could have the hook write a marker file when `/new` is called, and check for that marker during startup to know we just transitioned.\n\nBut the cleanest solution is to skip the marker file approach entirely and instead read the previous session's transcript from the session store during startup, then inject that context into the new session. The hook's `event.context` contains `sessionEntry` with the previous session's ID and file path, which gives me everything I need to locate and load that transcript.\n\nHowever, there's a timing issue: the hook fires when `/new` is called, but the session context has already been cleared by that point. Looking at the event structure more carefully, there's a `previousSessionEntry` field that should contain the session data from before the reset, which is what I actually need to access. The real issue is that after the session resets, the next time the agent runs it has no memory of what came before. I need a way to pass the previous session's context into the new session.\n\nI'm considering creating a hook that fires on `command:new` to save the session context to a file, then having the agent check for that file on startup and inject its contents. This approach has some overhead since it runs on every startup, but it's straightforward to implement. Alternatively, I could modify the agent startup script directly to handle this injection, though I'd need to verify that approach actually works with OpenClaw's constraints.","thinkingSignature":"d8141ef46b5237b0a4c13278991572937c4e834a647ae8e2003518fda2ec01cf"},{"type":"text","text":"\nNow I have a clear picture. The `session-memory` hook saves to a dated memory file, but nothing auto-injects it into the next session. I need to:\n\n1. Create a hook that fires on `command:new` to save the previous session to a well-known file (`memory/LAST_SESSION.md`)\n2. Modify the session startup to inject that file's content\n\nLet me scaffold the custom hook:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nq8v317w4mui_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command"