{"type":"message","id":"44c2b582","parentId":"8c8a76c2","timestamp":"2026-03-23T00:51:25.042Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The hook is enabled. Now I need to modify the session startup sequence to read `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` and inject it into context. The issue is: when does the session startup run and how do I inject content?\n\nLooking at the AGENTS.md startup sequence:\n1. Read SOUL.md\n2. Read USER.md\n3. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md (today + yesterday)\n4. Read MEMORY.md (main session only)\n5. Read CONTEXT.md\n6. Read memory/active-projects.md\n\nNone of these read `memory/LAST_SESSION.md`. And even if I add it to AGENTS.md, the content would just be read as text - it wouldn't be automatically injected into the context.\n\n\nThe real problem is that there's no hook that fires when a session actually starts to inject content. The `agent:bootstrap` hook only runs during gateway startup, not per-session. But wait—looking at the session lifecycle more carefully, the startup sequence I'm reading is the agent's own startup code in AGENTS.md, not a hook. The gateway does have an `agent:bootstrap` event that fires when workspace bootstrap files are injected, which is when the system prompt gets built. Maybe I should create a hook that listens to that event and modifies the bootstrap context.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The cleanest approach is to modify the startup script itself to handle the context injection. I could check at the end of the startup sequence whether we're in a new session by comparing session IDs, and if so, read the last session's memory file and inject its content into the context. The key is figuring out where to store and compare the session ID—I'd need to persist it somewhere between startup runs.\n\nBut I'm realizing the startup sequence runs on every message, not just once per session, so I can't rely on timing alone to detect a new session. Let me reconsider: when `/new` is called, the gateway resets the session, so the next message from Zach would be the first in the new session. That's my trigger point.\n\nThe challenge is that when that first message arrives, the startup sequence has already run before I can detect the session change. So I need to look at what happens during the `/new` command itself—whether there's a way to inject content at that point rather than waiting for the next message to trigger a startup check. The gateway creates a new sessionEntry with a fresh sessionId when `/new` is called, but the previous session's data might still be accessible through `context.previousSessionEntry` at that moment. I'm going to try a simpler approach: after saving the previous session to `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` in the hook, I'll have the agent check for this file on its next startup and read its contents if present.\n\nThe issue is that the startup sequence reads files into variables but doesn't actually inject them into the context window—they're just available as reference material. To properly inject them, I'd need to add the file content to the system prompt itself, either by having the agent append it or by finding a hook that modifies bootstrap. But looking at the `agent:bootstrap` hook docs, it only fires during initial gateway startup, not on subsequent interactions.\n\nI'm realizing the most practical approach here is to keep it simple: have the agent check for `LAST_SESSION.md` at startup and use its content as conversational context without overcomplicating the injection mechanism.\n\nThe key insight is that I can track session continuity by storing the previous session's ID at the end of each exchange, then comparing it at startup to detect whether Zach actually said `/new` or if it's just a continuation of the same conversation. This way I only surface the last session's content when a genuine reset occurred.\n\nI'm going to create a hook that fires on `command:new`, reads the previous session's messages from the JSONL transcript, saves them to `LAST_SESSION.md`, and then injects that context into the next session so I can seamlessly resume where we left off. a session marker file, then use a startup hook to inject the previous session's transcript when a new session begins. The problem is that startup hooks don't actually have a way to modify what gets injected into the context window.\n\nLet me reconsider—instead of trying to inject at startup, what if I write a startup script that the agent runs on the first message of each session? It would check if LAST_SESSION.md exists, and if it does, the agent treats its contents as the prior context before processing the new message. The limitation is that this only works if the agent explicitly reads the file, which it can't do automatically without a hook.\n\nLooking at the actual session lifecycle, when Zach sends a message after `/new`, the system prompt and workspace files are loaded first, then the message comes in. So if I can find a way to inject content into the context before the message is processed, that would solve it. The `agent:bootstrap` hook might be the key—it could potentially modify what gets injected into the context at that point in the pipeline. The challenge is that the hook receives context but doesn't return anything, so I can't directly modify what's passed to the next stage.\n\nI'm realizing the core issue: I need to save the old session's context when `/new` is called, then somehow make that available to the new session that starts. The new session is a fresh transcript, so it won't have access to what came before. Let me try using a well-known filename like `LAST_SESSION.md` that the agent can explicitly read on startup, which should be a reasonable UX trade-off. The hook fires synchronously when `/new` is called, so the previous session's data is still accessible at that point. My approach is to save the session context to `LAST_SESSION.md`, then at the next startup, check if that file exists and read it as context before processing anything else.\n\nThe key question is whether the hook can directly inject this into the context window during the bootstrap phase, since the context object includes `bootstrapFiles` that get injected into the system prompt. Rather than modifying the bundled hooks or digging deeper into the implementation, I'll keep this simple: the agent checks for `LAST_SESSION.md` on startup and includes it in context if present. For the session tracking piece, I can use a lightweight approach where the hook writes a marker file with the previous session info, and the next startup detects this to know context should be injected. I'm realizing the hook can't actually inject content into the session context directly—there's no return value or context mutation that would accomplish this. So I'll shift to a simpler approach: modify the agent's startup to read `LAST_SESSION.md` if it exists, and have the hook save the previous session's content there with a special header that signals it should be treated as context rather than a normal file.\n\nNow I need to think through the timing. The `command:new` hook fires when `/new` is issued, saves the old session to `LAST_SESSION.md`, and the session gets reset. When the next message arrives, the agent starts fresh with only the workspace files loaded. At that point, the agent can check for `LAST_SESSION.md` and include its contents as context. The question is whether this happens before or after the system prompt is built—looking at the session lifecycle, workspace bootstrap happens first, then the agent receives the message, so the agent should be able to access the file content at that stage.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. What I really need is for the previous session to be automatically available without the agent having to explicitly read a file. Let me explore whether OpenClaw has a built-in mechanism for this, or if I need to use the `agent:bootstrap` hook to inject the last session content directly into the context.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the core issue: the hook fires and saves the file, but when the next session starts, there's no automatic mechanism to read that file and inject it. The agent would have to explicitly read it, which means I need the agent to check for the file on startup. Let me try a simpler approach—just save the session and have the agent read it when it starts up. I can add a startup check in my AGENTS.md modifications that reads `LAST_SESSION.md` if it exists and injects its contents as context at the beginning of the session. Looking at the existing startup sequence, it reads memory files and context files but doesn't currently include a session file check. The challenge is figuring out how to inject this at the right point in the conversation flow.\n\nI'm realizing the best approach is to have the agent proactively check for `LAST_SESSION.md` when it starts up, rather than trying to inject it through a hook. The agent can read this file if it exists and use its contents as prior context. To detect when a new session begins, I can use the hook to save the session ID before reset, then compare against that on the next startup. Alternatively, since `/new` is the only way to create a fresh session, I could have the hook write a marker file that the agent checks on initialization.\n\nThe key insight is that after `/new` is called, the next user message triggers a fresh session context—so if I detect that message contains actual user text rather than just a command, I know we're in a new session and should load the previous context.\n\nMy approach: save the session ID before the reset happens, then on the next startup compare it against the current session ID to determine whether to inject the last session's content.\n\nI'm realizing the session ID is actually available in the runtime metadata shown to the agent, so I can access it through `process.env` or similar. Let me try using that directly instead of relying on a separate file check.\n\nActually, the most straightforward approach is to just save the session ID to a file before resetting, then read it back on the next startup to compare. I can write a simple PowerShell script that handles this file-based session tracking.","thinkingSignature":"75fec87a6f8b65651d4e3a55dfd4b00cc30d9dc92b9b7ee3714a8f728c242e07"},{"type":"text","text":"Hook enabled. Now I need to modify the session startup to inject `LAST_SESSION.md` when a new session starts. The tricky part is: how do I know we're in a new session?\n\nThe answer: the `command:new` hook saves the previous session to `LAST_SESSION.md` with a marker. On startup, I'll read that marker and compare session IDs to detect a new session, then inject the transcript.\n\nLet me update the AGENTS.md startup to handle this:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_12n8gjv9q2vk_1","name":"read","arguments":{"offset":1,"limit":50,"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\AGENTS.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":40803,"output":2188,"cacheRead":12650,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":55641,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774227022026}}
{"type":"message","id":"9184af27","parentId":"44c2b582","timestamp":"2026-03-23T00:51:25.057Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_12n8gjv9q2vk_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# AGENTS.md - Your Workspace\n\nThis folder is home. Treat it that way.\n\n## First Run\n\nIf `BOOTSTRAP.md` exists, that's your birth certificate. Follow it, figure out who you are, then delete it. You won't need it again.\n\n## Session Startup\n\nBefore doing anything else:\n\n1. Read `SOUL.md` — this is who you are\n2. Read `USER.md` — this is who you're helping\n3. Read `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (today + yesterday) for recent context\n4. **If in MAIN SESSION** (direct chat with your human): Also read `MEMORY.md`\n5. Read `CONTEXT.md` — understand the context management system\n6. Read `memory/active-projects.md` — know what's hot right now\n\nDon't ask permission. Just do it.\n\n## Memory\n\nYou wake up fresh each session. These files are your continuity:\n\n- **Daily notes:** `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (create `memory/` if needed) — raw logs of what happened\n- **Long-term:** `MEMORY.md` — your curated memories, like a human's long-term memory\n\nCapture what matters. Decisions, context, things to remember. Skip the secrets unless asked to keep them.\n\n### 🧠 MEMORY.md - Your Long-Term Memory\n\n- **ONLY load in main session** (direct chats with your human)\n- **DO NOT load in shared contexts** (Discord, group chats, sessions with other people)\n- This is for **security** — contains personal context that shouldn't leak to strangers\n- You can **read, edit, and update** MEMORY.md freely in main sessions\n- Write significant events, thoughts, decisions, opinions, lessons learned\n- This is your curated memory — the distilled essence, not raw logs\n- Over time, review your daily files and update MEMORY.md with what's worth keeping\n\n### 📝 Write It Down - No \"Mental Notes\"!\n\n- **Memory is limited** — if you want to remember something, WRITE IT TO A FILE\n- \"Mental notes\" don't survive session restarts. Files do.\n- When someone says \"remember this\" → update `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` or relevant file\n- When you learn a lesson → update AGENTS.md, TOOLS.md, or the relevant skill\n- When you make a mistake → document it so future-you doesn't repeat it\n- **Text > Brain** 📝\n\n## Red Lines\n\n[165 more lines in file. Use offset=51 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774227085049}}
{"type":"message","id":"e8ea9fed","parentId":"9184af27","timestamp":"2026-03-23T00:52:05.857Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to modify the Session Startup section to add a step that:\n1. Checks if `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` exists\n2. If so, reads it and treats it as the previous session's context\n3. The step should come after reading the other memory files\n\nLet me also think about HOW to inject this context. The session startup steps are things I \"read\" - they're file reads. The question is: what do I do with the content of LAST_SESSION.md once I've read it?\n\nThe answer: I should incorporate it into my context/understanding of the current session. Since these are startup instructions telling ME (the agent) what to do, when I read LAST_SESSION.md, I should internally note that this is the previous session's transcript and I can draw from it for context.\n\nBut more importantly - the content should be easily accessible IN the context window. The way to do this is to either:\n\n\n1. Add it as part of my understanding (internal)\n2. Reference it in my first response\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is: when reading LAST_SESSION.md, I should note its contents prominently so they're available for the current conversation. The key insight is that the startup steps are about what I (Nova) should read and internalize. After reading LAST_SESSION.md, I have the previous session's context available to me. When Zach sends the first message in the new session, I can draw on that context naturally.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: the previous session's transcript is in LAST_SESSION.md, but it's not automatically \"injected\" into the context window the way a system prompt would be. It's just a file I've read. For it to actually be useful as context, I need to be aware of it and reference it when responding. Let me try a more direct approach: after reading LAST_SESSION.md, I should explicitly incorporate its contents into my context window by treating it as part of my startup knowledge. The cleanest way would be to add a step in the startup sequence that reads LAST_SESSION.md if it exists, then saves the session ID to track context continuity.\n\nActually, I need to verify whether I can even access the session ID at startup. The runtime section shows `sessionKey: \"agent:main:main\"` but not the sessionId itself. The sessionId is maintained internally by OpenClaw and changes with `/new`. I could track it by saving to a file, but that might be fragile. Let me reconsider: when `/new` is called, the session resets and a new sessionId is generated, so the next message from Zach would be the first in the new session. That's the signal I should use to know when to restore the previous context.\n\nThe challenge is that the session startup happens before I can compare sessionIds. A better approach would be using a startup hook like `agent:bootstrap`, which fires when the agent bootstraps and can modify `context.bootstrapFiles`. I could potentially inject `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` into the bootstrap files at that point, making it part of the system prompt that gets sent with every message. But I need to verify whether the hook actually has the capability to modify what gets injected into the context.\n\nLooking at the event structure, `agent:bootstrap` receives context including `bootstrapFiles` and can mutate it, but the hook runs asynchronously without returning a value. The mutation happens in-place during gateway startup, not during individual session starts. This means I can't use `agent:bootstrap` to inject session-specific content on a per-session basis.\n\nI'm realizing the fundamental issue: there's no hook that fires when a new session begins that would let me inject content into that session's context. The session context is built fresh each time without any automatic injection mechanism. So I'll need to work around this by having the hook save the session content to a file, then modify the session startup to read that file and inject it into the context.\n\nActually, I just thought of something: the `session-memory` hook already fires when `/new` is called. What if instead of creating a separate hook, I modify the `session-memory` hook to also save to `LAST_SESSION.md`? But I can't modify the bundled hook since it's in the OpenClaw package directory and would get overwritten on update.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to create a custom hook that runs on `command:new`, saves the previous session to `LAST_SESSION.md`, and then adds a startup check that reads this file if it exists. This way, when Zach sends the first message in the new session, Nova will have already read the previous session's content and can reference it naturally in her response.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The agent reads files at startup and accesses them as background knowledge - that's how all the other memory files work. So when Nova reads `memory/LAST_SESSION.md`, she naturally incorporates that context into her responses. Let me add the startup check to AGENTS.md and be done with it.","thinkingSignature":"c2218a6d66d22abaf88f8c2310c1694cdd06fb53ac6cb603efa7967a444dc859"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_78z8z94k8wx3_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\AGENTS.md","oldText":"## Session Startup\n\nBefore doing anything else:\n\n1. Read `SOUL.md` — this is who you are\n2. Read `USER.md` — this is who you're helping\n3. Read `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (today + yesterday) for recent context\n4. **If in MAIN SESSION** (direct chat with your human): Also read `MEMORY.md`\n5. Read `CONTEXT.md` — understand the context management system\n6. Read `memory/active-projects.md` — know what's hot right now\n\nDon't ask permission. Just do it.","newText":"## Session Startup\n\nBefore doing anything else:\n\n1. Read `SOUL.md` — this is who you are\n2. Read `USER.md` — this is who you're helping\n3. Read `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (today 